{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/00340580928/1945081701/0289.xml":{"full_text":"CHEST\nFACTS\nBy W. C. FIELDER\nIn a recent letter to the editor of\nthe Beacon Journal, I notifced that an\nindividual stated that he had quit con\ntributing to the War Chest because\nthe hospitals received an allotment\nfrom the Chest. I would like to explain\nthat no hospitals received an allotment\nfrom the Chest. I would like to explain\nthat no hospital receives one cent from\nthe Chest, except in cases where the\npatient is unable to pay. Each year\nthe trustees of the United War Chest\nset aside a certain amount for this pur\npose. The Chest's Central Investiga\ntion Bureau, after a thorough investi\ngation to determine whether or not\nthe patient is able to pay, certifies thp\ncase to the Chest and the hospitals are\npaid for the exact service rendered.\nThis is the only money the hospitals\nreceive from the Chest. (Members of\norganized labor have received a large\namount of the money paid out for such\ncases in the last three years.\nI would like to make this statement\nregarding the crowded conditions in the\nvarious' hospitals in Summit County.\nNot only is the Children\u2019s Hospital\novercrowded but all of them n<?ed ad\nditional facilities. The Edwin Shaw\nSanatorium should be twice its present\nsize to accommodate the number of\ncases now needing care in Summit\nCounty. As an organized group it is\nour duty to see that these conditions\n3re remedied. Who knows\u2014it may be\nyour child or my child, a relative, or a\nmerrtber of the family who needs this\ncare and the present facilities are not\nsufficient to give them the care needed.\nMany people who find themselves\ntemporarily \u201cup against it\u201d have re\nceived assistance through the Chest.\nThere are many things the public\nshould know in regard to the opera\ntion of the Chest.\nThe National War Fund and the lo\ncal War Chest have been endorsed by\nthe National CIO, and AFL, the Broth\nerhood of Railroad Trainmen and by\nthe local labor organiztions. Organized\nlabor not only participates in the local\nWar Chest but is a part of it, and has\na say in all matters pertaining to the\nChest including the policies and rules\nset-up from time to time governing the\nexpenditure of the money. The mouthy\ncontributed to the Chest is put there\nfor the sole purpose of helping the\nneedy, our armed forces, and'our allies\nand to make this a better community\nand a better country to live in. So let\u2019s\nnot do anything to detour us from the\naims and principles for which we are\nfighting.\nOf each dollar contributed to the\nChest 26c goes for the welfare and\nentertainment of the armed forces of\nthe United States and Our Allies; 15c\nto United Nations Refugee Relief and\nemergencies; 4c for local War Serv\nOURS IS THE CHOICE\n(Continued from Page One)\npower, authority and money to tackle the job, they refused\nto raise their voices.\nTimid? No! It just wasn\u2019t done in t}ie best of vicious\nCircles. Public welfare is fine with private welfare and priv\nate welfare should get along well with public welfare, but,\nafter all, what would private welfare do if public welfare did\nmost of it in the first place?\nPretty confusing? So was our community on Pearl\nHarbor Day.\n\nThere has been a lot of. talk about labor isolating itself\nfrom the community, but very little talk about the commun\nity isolating itself from labor.\nPerhaps the words \u201clabor\u201d and \u201ccommunity\u201d have been\nused too loosely in 'this respect, but the fact remains that\nthose in control of community social services have be^n too\nlong removed from the social needs of the people.\nThere has been too much Confusion, too much competi\ntion and too much timidity. Our social agencies were not\nready when millions of citizens shifted to war production\nand almost broke the seams of our communities.\nThey were unprepared for war, and now they are un\nprepared for peace.\n\nIt is true that some progress was made during the past\nfour years. We, of labor, must take some small credit for it.\nbut many social workers and leaders have been thinking\nmore constructively, speaking more courageously and acting\nmore affirmatively.\nBut it isn\u2019t enough.\nUnless we pool our combined resources now for the\ncommon good of all, V-J Day will find our communities un\nable to cope with the problems of potential unemployment,\nracial tensions, veterans\u2019 aid, housing, medical care and\nothers.\nSugar-coated sentimentality will not gear us to action.\nOnly a positive program of representative community or\nganization. Courageously promoted, will help.\nOnly the full utilization of Federal, State and commun\nity facilities in a coordinated voluntary political and legisla\ntive approach to the'health and welfare needs' of the people\nwill do the job.\nices; 31c raor Family Welfare, Child\nCare, and Hospitalization; 21c for\nGroup-Work, Youth and Community\nServices; 3c for the War Chest. This\n3c is used for the administration of the\nChest office, for paying the clerical\nhelp, and campaign expenses.\nAfter all\u2014this is our Chest, yours and\nmine. Each individual in the commun\nity is a member and a part of this or\nganization. If there is any question you\n.would like to have ahswercd or any\nproblem with which you need help, call\nthe Chest office. We will be more than\nglad to be of any assistance possible.\nFrom time to time this column will\ncarry an article explaining the Chest.\nReconversion\n(Continued from Page One)\ncatcd by the Congress of Industrial\nOrganizations before Congress ad\njourned for vacation will be presented\nagain.\nThe points of the CIO program,\nwhich are designed to protect Labor\nduring the reconversion period, are:\n1. Increasing the present minimum\nwage from 40 to 65 cents per hour,\nwith a gradual further increase to 75\ncents per hour during the next two\nyears.\n2. To break the Little Steel Wage\nFormula by authorizing a 20 per cent\nincrease in pay to offset a similar in\ncrease in living costs.\n3. Unemployment compensation pro\nproviding for a maximum of $25 per\nweek for a period of 26 weeks as ad\nvocated by President Truman.\n4. The creation of a permanent Fair\nEmployment Practices Commission.\n5. The enlargement of the Social\nSecurity program as contained in the\nWagner-Murray-Dingell Bill.\n6. The passage of the Murray-Pat\nton Full Employment Bill as the\nmeans of providing 60,000,000 postwar\njobs.\nHow hard Akron will be hit by the\ncancellation of war contracts is not\nknown. It is estimated in some cir\ncles that as many as 35,000 or 40,000\nworkers will be idle for at least a tem\nporary period.\nIndustries have indicated that they\nwill make the necessary changes from\nwar to peace production as quickly as\npossible. Some departments or small\nindustries may switch over in only a\nfew days. Others may require several\nmonths.\nHomemakers, There's a 10-Year Guarantee On This\nSUPREME S,aosnt FURNACE\nr\nFree heating estimate\nby O\u2019NeiFs Heating\nExperts if you dial\nBlA13h\n*8975\nMassive 1 -Pc.\nRadiator\nExtra-size Combustion\nDome\nEasy-shake Duplex\nGrates\nExtra Roomy, Deep\nAsh Pit\nNow when you no longer need\nheat is the time to plan ahead\n.to get your home set lor\nnext winter\u2019s cold apell with a\ndependable furnace. This su\npreme has been constructed to our\nexact specifications by one of the\nnation\u2019s three largest furnace mak- 1\ners. It will give you dependable,\nmaximum long-life comfort and\nservice this winter and for many\nwinters to come. S\nFURNACES\u2014FOURTH FLOOR*\nli\nThe M. O\u2019NEIL Company\n(Continued from Page 1)\ning reconversion by approving Presi-|\nderft Truman\u2019s recommendations for\nemergency supplementation of inade\nquate state unemployment compensa\ntion, by adopting legislation for high\ner minimum wage 'standards, by en\nacting the vital Wagner postwar\nhousing bill and by extending the na\ntion\u2019s social security system as pro\nvided under the Wagner-Murray-Din\ngell bill.\nThe council declared it will amplify\nits recommendations on each of the\npoints of its program with declara\ntions on specific policies to be drafted\nduring the current meeting.\nAFL President William Green said\nthe council had decided to deal with\nthe reconversion problem first be\ncause it is the key to postwar recov\nery. On this point the council de\nclared\n\u201cAmeiaca is now getting too little\nreconversion. Unless preparations for\nresumption of peacetime production\nare speeded up, it may be too late to\navoid a major postwar depression.\nUnless more adequate provision is\npromptly made for human needs dur\ning reconversion, peace may bring\neconomic disaster t<^ -the^ American\npeople.\n\u2018'This tragedy must be averted. The\npeace to which all Americans look\nforward after four years of war and\nsacrifice must not bear bitter fruit.\nTHe millions of American young men\nin uniform who have uiylergone the\nagony of modern warfare must find\nopportunity, not breadlines, when they\nreturn home. The millions of war\nworkers who have labored to tHe\npoint of -exhaustion in a victory pro\nduction drive which broke all records\nmust not be cast off with heartless\ndisregard of whether or not they will\nbe able to find another job.\n\u201cAmeriea cannot afford to let these\nthings happen because, if we do, the\nAmerican way of life will be obliter\nate^ just as certainly as it would have\nbeen if Hitler had won the war. But\nwe won the war and we can also win\nthe peace if we plan intelligently and\nact boldly and confidently.\u201d\nMr. Green announced that the exec\nutive council had appointed Secretary\nTreasurer George Meany and Vice\nPresident William C. Doherty to\nserve as the AFL\u2019s fraternal delegates\nto the convention of the British\nI\nBilbo\n(Continued from Page 1)\nof your latter to two citiaen* of\nUnited State*, dated July fth.\nthis\n\"My Dear